HE WOULD BE EMBARRASSED TO HAVE HIS FRIENDS COME OVER TO WHERE HE LIVED.
HE DIDN'T WANT TO BE DIFFERENT AND HE BELIEVED THAT LIVING IN A LIBRARY.
HE BELIEVED LIVING IN A LIBRARY WAS VERY DIFFERENT.
HE WAS ABLE TO RUN AROUND THE LIBRARY AND SHOUT AND SCREAM AT NIGHT WHEN THE LIBRARY WAS CLOSED.
IF HE HAD A QUESTION AT ANY TIME HE COULD GO INTO THE LIBRARY AND RESEARCH IT.
WHEN HE BECAME A PROFESSOR HE WAS PROUD TO SHOW HIS FATHER HIS OFFICE DOOR.

WHEN HE WAS YOUNG HE THOUGHT HIS FAMILY WAS RICH.
HE FAMILY DISAGREED AND TOLD HIM THEY WERE POOR.
HIS FATHER GOT A JOB AS A CUSTODIAN IN A LIBRARY.
HE MOVED HIS FAMILY INTO THE LIBRARY, WHICH WAS CUSTOMARY.
HIS FATHER TOOK PRIDE IN HIS WORK.
HE EVEN WAXED THE TOPS OF BOOKSHELVES.
THE LIBRARY HE WORKED AT WAS ALWAYS CLEAN AND THE FLOORS WERE WAXED.
HE NEVER INVITED HIS FRIENDS TO VISIT HIS HOUSE.
HE WANTED TO BE NORMAL AND DID NOT BELIEVE THAT LIVING IN A LIBRARY WAS NORMAL.
HE GREW TO LOVE READING AND WOULD OFTEN READ LATE AT NIGHT.
HE COULD RUN THROUGH THE LIBRARY AND BE AS LOUD AS HE WANTED AFTER THE LIBRARY WAS CLOSED.
WHEN HE GREW UP HE BECAME A PROFESSOR.
HE WAS THE FIRST PERSON IN HIS FAMILY TO GRADUATE FROM COLLEGE.
HE BROUGHT HIS FATHER TO HIS OFFICE TO SHOW HIM WHERE HE WORKED.
HE RESPONDED QUIETLY WITH A NOD.
PROFESSOR CLARK DOESN'T BELIEVE THAT HE WOULD HAVE DONE WHAT HE HAD DONE WITHOUT HIS EXPERIENCE GROWING UP IN A LIBRARY.
WHEN HE HAD A QUESTION AT NIGHT HE WOULD GO DOWN INTO THE LIBRARY TO RESEARCH AND READ.
